ree Canadian provinces combined,', ' according to Business Insider\'s Hillary Hoffower.', 'The figure is now almost twice that.\n', 'On top of this list is the chairman of Samsung Group, Lee Kun-Hee, who is worth an estimated $20.3 billion, according to Forbes.\n', 'The nation\'s richest man is Giovanni Ferrero, the secretive billionaire behind the Ferrero Group', 'makers of Nutella and Ferrero Rocher chocolates. He has an estimated net worth of $32 billion, according to Bloomberg.'),
(38, 'TOP 10 CHEAPEST COUNTRIES IN THE WORLD', 'The local purchasing power of South Africa is 26.9% higher and Rent is 87.5% cheaper Groceries are 71% cheaper and Local goods and services are 65.8% cheaperSouth Africa is the cheapest country to live or retire.', 'The local purchasing power of India is 20.9% lower and Rent is 95.2% cheaper Groceries are 74.4% cheaper and Local goods and services are 74.9% cheaper India is the most populous country among the 50 cheapest, homes to 1.25 billion residents.', 'The local purchasing power of Kosovo is 33.8% lower and Rent is 91.5% lower Groceries are 75.8% cheaper and Local goods and services are 72.6% cheaper Kosovo is located in Eastern Europe and borders Serbia', 'The local purchasing power of Saudi Arabia is 33.6% higher but Rent is 85.9% cheaper Groceries are 56.4% cheaper and Local goods and services are 49.4% cheaper Groceries are more expensive in this desert country than most other cheapest countries, as are consumer goods', 'The local purchasing power of Kazakhstan is 38.2% lower Rent is 88.9% cheaper in the countryGroceries are 74.8% cheaper and Local goods and services are 68.7% cheaper Kazakhstan borders Russia and China, ', 'The local purchasing power of Zambia is 50% higher and Rent is 68.1% cheaper in Zambia. Groceries are 59.1% cheaper and Local goods and services are 44.6% cheap. Zambia actually has the highest rent of any of the 50 countries in these rankings.', 'The local purchasing power of Oman is 57.5% higher and Rent is 71.7% cheaper in the country Groceries are 48.9% cheaper and Local goods and services are 44.4% cheaper', 'The local purchasing power of Paraguay is 49% lower and Rent is 91.7% cheaper in the country Groceries are 75.3% cheaper and Local goods and services are 69.7% cheaper', 'Local purchasing of Czech Republic power is 8.4% lower Rent is 87.8% cheaper in the countries Groceries are 63% cheaper and Local goods and services are 57.7% cheaper.', 'The local purchasing power of Macedonia is 49.7% lower Rent is 94% cheaper in the country and Groceries are 73.3% cheaper. Local goods and services are 68.6% cheaper', 'SouthAfrica.jpg', 'India.jpg', 'Kosovo.jpg', 'SaudiArabia.jpg', 'Kazakhstan.jpg', 'Zambia.jpg', 'Oman.jpg', 'Paraguay.jpg', 'CzechRepublic.jpg', 'Macedonia.jpg', 'COUNTRIES', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'South Africa', 'India', 'Kosovo', 'Saudi Arabia', 'Kazakhstan', 'Zambia', 'Oman', 'Paraguay', 'Czech Republic', 'Macedonia', 'It’s also the world’s largest producer of platinum, gold, and chromium, which goes far to enrich the country and its economy. This resulted in local purchasing power. Along with a higher local purchasing power, South Africa also offers lower prices on consumer goods and groceries, and rent costs\n that is typical of the 50 cheapest countries', 'In the major city of Cape Town, for instance, monthly expenses total just under $400 while the average rent costs are reflected by the typical price to rent a one-bedroom in Durban of around $280 a month.', 'Its major industries include textiles, chemicals, and food processing. India also has a relatively high local purchasing power in the major cities surveyed. Living in India can be cheap it has the second-lowest rent index of the 50 cheapest countries (after neighbor Nepal).', 'India also has some of the lowest prices for consumer goods and groceries, with typical monthly expenses for these priced around $285 a month for a single person living in Kolkata.\n', 'Albania and Macedonia. It has a population of 1.9 million, and mineral mining and construction materials are the major industries in Kosovo.', 'When it comes to costs, Kosovo scores the best on consumer goods and groceries — in the capital of Pristina, expenses for a single person are just $324 a month. Rent costs are also low at just $275 a month for a one-bedroom apartment.\n', 'But this Middle  Eastern nation is fairly wealthy, thanks to its strong oil industry centered on crude oil, petroleum refining, and petrochemicals.', ' Plus, Saudi Arabia has a higher GDP per capita of $24,161, according to the World Bank. This helps give Saudi Arabia a local purchasing power that even beats out New York City.', 'and has a population of 18.2 million people. The local economy relies on Kazakhstan’s natural resources like oil, coal and iron ore.', 'Kazakhstan’s cheap living is most apparent in its costs for groceries and consumer goods, which are lower than most of the 50 cheapest nations.', 'Yet, this African nation landed at No. 6 among the cheapest countries thanks to its high local purchasing powers.', ' For those looking to relocate to a cheaper country, Zambia would offer both lower costs and local incomes high enough to help cover expenses.', 'Oman is a small nation with a population of 3.3 million that borders Saudi Arabia and the Arabian Sea', 'Like many of its Middle  Eastern neighbors, Oman is rich in oil and gas resources that make it a wealthy nation that has the highest local purchasing power in the top 50.\n', 'A South American nation with a population of 6.8 million, Paraguay’s main industries include sugar, cement, and textiles. The country has low costs across the board on rent, grocery and consumer goods', 'In the nation’s capital, Asunción, monthly expenses for a single person are just around $360 month, and rent for a single-bedroom flat is about $250.\n', 'The Czech Republic lands at No. 9 thanks to a balance between lower costs and a higher local purchasing power. This European country \nborders Germany, Austria, and Poland, and has a population of 10.6 million.', 'It has a higher GDP per capita (around $19,500), according to the World Bank, which means that locals can buy more with their incomes.', 'Rounding out the top 10 of the cheapest countries to live in or retire is Macedonia, which has one of the lowest rents of the 50 cheapest countries.', ' Groceries and consumer goods also cheap, which keeps costs low despite a middling local purchasing power. Macedonia is a